<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Gutierrezia sarothrae </i>and <i>G. microcephala </i>are low shrubs with thread-like, leaves that are facultatively drought- and winter-deciduous. Plants are summer to fall blooming and produce abundant seed crops. Seeds fall near parent plants where they form a seed bank. They need cold stratification or after-ripening and will germinate under warm, moist conditions. Plants develop deep taproots that can colonize areas with limited water or under drought conditions, and populations sizes may vary with drought cycles. Plants are also toxic to ungulates, though the seeds of <i>Gutierrezia </i>spp. are readily eaten by a wide variety of small birds and mammals (Bonneau 2000, Tirmenstein 1999f, Carey 1995d). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Gutierrezia sarothrae </i> and <i>G. microcephala </i>occur on moderately sloping hillsides, particularly south-facing slopes, and plateaus with undulating topography. Disturbances, including clearing, fire, grazing, or intermittent flooding, create conditions for seed establishment of these snakeweeds. Stands appear as early seral types, which may transition to longer-lived shrub and herb alliances after recovery from disturbance or drought.<br/>
<br/>
This alliance was cited as <i>Gutierrezia sarothrae</i> Provisional Shrubland Alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. It has been expanded to include either <i>G. microcephala </i>or <i>G. sarothrae </i>as the dominant shrub. When other shrubs are present, including in washes, other disturbance settings, and steep rocky slopes, key to those alliances first (e.g., <i>Ericameria teretifolia, Eriogonum fasciculatum - Viguiera parishii, Prunus fasciculata - Salazaria mexicana, Eriogonum wrightii - Eriogonum heermannii - Buddleja utahensis, Ephedra viridis </i>,or other alliances). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
