<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">This early seral type replaces other long-persisent types following fire or other disturbances, including <i>Artemisia tridentata,  Coleogyne ramosissima, Juniperus osteosperma, Larrea tridentata, Pinus monophylla, Yucca schidigera, Yucca brevifolia </i>Alliances, and other desert plant communities. Wind-dispersed seeds of <i>Gutierrezia </i>spp. from adjacent unburned areas can colonize burned sites, and soil-stored seeds also germinate. Post-fire, this alliance typically follows annual grasses, forbs, and short-lived perennials in one to two decades, though it may take only five years for this alliance to gain dominance in some sites including moister settings. Then it can take 40 or more years for other longer-lived types to rebound.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
